results.title: Cameroonian Roads
results.description:
Data on road surface type, condition and traffic volume were compiled by Tecsult for the AICD study led by the World Bank.  Roads data from the Cellule de Programmation (Ministry of Public Works) were reviewed and transport experts were consulted in an effort to derive estimates for all of the primary and secondary road network.

The following attributes were collected:
UNIFORM_ID: ID of the link,
ADM2_NAME: Name of the 1st level of administrative division (region),
ADM2_ID: ID of the administrative division,
ADM3_NAME: Name of the secondary administrative division (province),
ADM3_ID: ID of the secondary administrative division ,
ROAD_ID: ID of the road,
ROAD_NAME: Name of the road,
START_NODE: Name of the locality where the link starts,
END_NODE: Name of the locality where the link finishes,
LINK_NAME: Name of the link,
RD_TYPE: World Bank functional classification ,
LOCAL_CLS: Local classification,
LENGTH: Length of link (km),
ROAD_WIDTH: Width of road (m),
AADT_CODE: Classification of condition of traffic ,
AADT_VALUE: Value of condition of traffic,
AADT_SOURCE: Source of condition of traffic ,
SURF_TYPE_CODE: Classification of surface type ,
SURF_TYPE_VALUE: Value of surface type ,
SURF_TYPE_SOURCE: Source of surface type,
ROAD_COND_CODE: Classification of road condition ,
ROAD_COND_VALUE: Value of road condition ,
ROAD_COND_SOURCE: Source of road condition,
LANE_NB: Number of lanes,
AICD_REG: Roads providing essential regional connectivity as defined by AICD,
TAH: Trans-African Highway Corridors

Attribute values may be unknown (value = -99) for any of the descriptive characteristics.

results.title: Coral Bleaching Story Map
results.description: This map shows the effects of coral bleaching on worldwide reefs. Layers include reef areas, sampling stations, locations of artificial reefs, areas where mass bleaching events have already happened, and areas at risk for bleaching events. By viewing this map, I hope that others will understand the magnitude of the threat that our reefs are facing, and the how severe the overall threat of global warming. Because of increased water temperatures, corals lose the vital algae they rely on for protection and a food source. Without them, they are left weak and vulnerable, and die majority of the time. Coral reefs directly contribute the the health of our oceans and our planet, and it is imperative that action is quickly taken to halt contributions to climate change. This is just one of the countless impacts of climate change around the world, and it is our job to fix it.
results.snippet: This story map shows the affects of coral bleaching on worldwide warm water coral reefs
results.accessInformation: National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), NOAA Coral Reef Watch Program, MarineCadastre.gov, National Ocean Service (NOS), Office for Coastal Management (OCM), The Nature Conservancy
